<p>Just say I have a value of type <code>uint64_t</code> seen as sequence of octets (1 octet = 8-bit). The <code>uint64_t</code> value is known containing only one <em>set bit</em> at a MSB position. Thus, the <code>uint64_t</code> value can be in one of the following binary representations:</p>  <pre><code>00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 10000000  pos = 7 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 10000000 00000000  pos = 15 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 10000000 00000000 00000000  pos = 23 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 10000000 00000000 00000000 00000000  pos = 31 00000000 00000000 00000000 10000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000  pos = 39 00000000 00000000 10000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000  pos = 47 00000000 10000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000  pos = 55 10000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000000  pos = 63 </code></pre>  <p>I need a fast function that returns the <em>set bit</em> position, but returns 0 if there is no bit that is set.</p>  <p>If possible, I want it without neither looping nor branching.</p>